aseline_link_bcd_table">
              See full compatibility
            </a>
          </li>
          <li>
            <a href=3D"https://survey.alchemer.com/s3/7634825/MDN-baseline-=
feedback?page=3D%2Fen-US%2Fdocs%2FWeb%2FJavaScript%2FReference%2FGlobal_Obj=
ects%2FDate&amp;level=3Dhigh" data-glean-id=3D"baseline_link_feedback" clas=
s=3D"feedback-link" target=3D"_blank" rel=3D"noreferrer">
              Report feedback
            </a>
          </li>
        </ul>
      </div>
    </details><!--?--> <section class=3D"content-section">
   =20
    <p>JavaScript <strong><code>Date</code></strong> objects represent a si=
ngle moment in time in a platform-independent format. <code>Date</code> obj=
ects encapsulate an integral number that represents milliseconds since the =
midnight at the beginning of January 1, 1970, UTC (the <em>epoch</em>).</p>
<div class=3D"notecard note">
<p><strong>Note:</strong>
With the introduction of the <a href=3D"https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US=
/docs/Web/JavaScript/Reference/Global_Objects/Temporal"><code>Temporal</cod=
e></a> API, the <code>Date</code> object is considered a legacy feature. Co=
nsider using <code>Temporal</code> for new code and migrate existing code o=
ver to it if possible (check the <a href=3D"https://developer.mozilla.org/e=
n-US/docs/Web/JavaScript/Reference/Global_Objects/Temporal#browser_compatib=
ility">browser compatibility</a>. We will be writing a usage guide soon!</p=
>
</div>
  </section>
