<p>There are various methods that allow you to interact with the timestamp =
stored in the date:</p>
<ul>
<li>You can interact with the timestamp value directly using the <a href=3D=
"https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/JavaScript/Reference/Global_O=
bjects/Date/getTime"><code>getTime()</code></a> and <a href=3D"https://deve=
loper.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/JavaScript/Reference/Global_Objects/Date/s=
etTime"><code>setTime()</code></a> methods.</li>
<li>The <a href=3D"https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/JavaScript/=
Reference/Global_Objects/Date/valueOf"><code>valueOf()</code></a> and <a hr=
ef=3D"https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/JavaScript/Reference/Glo=
bal_Objects/Date/Symbol.toPrimitive"><code>[Symbol.toPrimitive]()</code></a=
> (when passed <code>"number"</code>) methods =E2=80=94 which are automatic=
ally called in <a href=3D"https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/Java=
Script/Reference/Global_Objects/Number#number_coercion">number coercion</a>=
 =E2=80=94 return the timestamp, causing <code>Date</code> objects to behav=
e like their timestamps when used in number contexts.</li>
<li>All static methods (<a href=3D"https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs=
/Web/JavaScript/Reference/Global_Objects/Date/now"><code>Date.now()</code><=
/a>, <a href=3D"https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/JavaScript/Ref=
erence/Global_Objects/Date/parse"><code>Date.parse()</code></a>, and <a hre=
f=3D"https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/JavaScript/Reference/Glob=
al_Objects/Date/UTC"><code>Date.UTC()</code></a>) return timestamps instead=
 of <code>Date</code> objects.</li>
<li>The <a href=3D"https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/JavaScript/=
Reference/Global_Objects/Date/Date"><code>Date()</code></a> constructor can=
 be called with a timestamp as the only argument.</li>
</ul>
  </section><section class=3D"content-section" aria-labelledby=3D"date_comp=
onents_and_time_zones">
    <!--lit-part yKi6g5DVLwk=3D--><!--lit-node 0--><h3 id=3D"date_component=
s_and_time_zones" class=3D"heading"><!--lit-node 1--><a class=3D"heading-an=
chor" href=3D"https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/JavaScript/Refer=
ence/Global_Objects/Date#date_components_and_time_zones">Date components an=
d time zones</a></h3><!--/lit-part-->
    <p>A date is represented internally as a single number, the <em>timesta=
mp</em>. When interacting with it, the timestamp needs to be interpreted as=
 a structured date-and-time representation. There are always two ways to in=
terpret a timestamp: as a local time or as a Coordinated Universal Time (UT=
C), the global standard time defined by the World Time Standard. The local =
timezone is not stored in the date object, but is determined by the host en=
vironment (user's device).</p>
<div class=3D"notecard note">
<p><strong>Note:</strong>
UTC should not be confused with the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wik=
i/Greenwich_Mean_Time" class=3D"external" target=3D"_blank">Greenwich Mean =
Time</a> (GMT), because they are not always equal =E2=80=94 this is explain=
ed in more detail in the linked Wikipedia page.</p>
</div>
<p>For example, the timestamp 0 represents a unique instant in history, but=
 it can be interpreted in two ways:</p>
<ul>
<li>As a UTC time, it is midnight at the beginning of January 1, 1970, UTC,=
</li>
<li>As a local time in New York (UTC-5), it is 19:00:00 on December 31, 196=
9.</li>
</ul>
<p>The <a href=3D"https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/JavaScript/R=
eference/Global_Objects/Date/getTimezoneOffset"><code>getTimezoneOffset()</=
code></a> method returns the difference between UTC and the local time in m=
inutes. Note that the timezone offset does not only depend on the current t=
imezone, but also on the time represented by the <code>Date</code> object, =
because of daylight saving time and historical changes. In essence, the tim=
ezone offset is the offset from UTC time, at the time represented by the <c=
ode>Date</code> object and at the location of the host environment.</p>
<p>There are two groups of <code>Date</code> methods: one group gets and se=
ts various date components by interpreting the timestamp as a local time, w=
hile the other uses UTC.</p>
